{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778079391,"nonce":"z77Y2ge54MS/8d5jjq+T9ViK8YI=","title":"Caveat: 'just add LEQG aggregation' is not a backdoor to flavor-(b) training","message":"Load-bearing methodology caveat surfaced as tension #2 of Synthesis 5 (`/Users/mll/Documents/Claude/Projects/clench/synthesis-5.md`). Filed here so future agents/reviewers don't reach for LEQG as a shortcut around adversary-class redesign.\n\n## The question\n\nIf (d) LEQG-via-Whittle is formally dual to (b) H∞ model-class min-max, why does our project distinguish between them?\n\n## Three layers (the answer)\n\nThe duality `(d) ≅ (b)` is a theoretical statement under specific conditions (Gaussian noise, quadratic cost, infinite-horizon LQ structure, a specific γ-correspondence between LEQG risk-sensitivity and H∞ disturbance-energy bound). It does NOT trivially extend to sample-based training in nonlinear settings.\n\n### 1. Asymptotic LQ duality has assumptions we partly violate\n- Nonlinear RNN policy.\n- Non-Gaussian losses (running_cost is L1-ish in places).\n- Finite horizon.\n- Empirical disturbance distribution from PGD, not Gaussian.\n\n### 2. The deepest problem — duality is between (d) on a *specific* distribution and (b) on a *corresponding* model class\n\nIf you implement (d) by sample-based LEQG `(1/γ) log E[exp(γ J)]` reweighting **on top of your existing flavor-(a) sampler** (parametric force trajectories), you get **LEQG of (a)**, not (d) ≅ (b). The reweighting only sharpens the tail of whatever distribution you already had. To realize the dual of (b), the sampler distribution must cover the model class — meaning **adversary-class redesign comes first**.\n\n\u003e **'Just add LEQG aggregation' is NOT a backdoor to (b). It's a backdoor to the LEQG-tilt of your existing (a)-class.**\n\nThe (d) ≅ (b) duality is a statement about what (d) *converges to* if (d) is run on the right distribution.\n\n### 3. Nonlinear / finite-horizon sanity\nEven with the right sample space, asymptotic LQ duality may not hold tightly for a nonlinear neural policy on a finite horizon. Empirical confirmation that (d) and (b) give comparable trained controllers in our setting is itself useful information.\n\n## Implication for the synthesis_review §11 sequence\n\nCurrent sequence (`results/part2_5/synthesis_review.md` §11):\n1. H∞ Riccati simulation\n2. Induced-gain `||T_{w→z}||_∞` on existing checkpoints\n3. H∞-Riccati teacher distillation\n4. `LinearDynamicsAdversary` with ΔA inner loop (the (b) lift)\n5. Damping calibration retraining\n6. (downgraded) LEQG aggregation\n\nLEQG (#6) being downgraded was the right call. **This issue clarifies why:** not because LEQG is a weak risk-sensitive method, but because **LEQG on a flavor-(a) distribution is not the dual of (b)**. Step #4 (adversary redesign) must come first; then LEQG becomes the natural sample-based realization of risk-sensitive (b)-style training, optionally on top of (b).\n\n## Decision rule for future agents\n\nWhenever 'let's just add LEQG' is proposed, ask first: **what sample space is LEQG operating on?**\n- If parametric forces (current rlrmp setup) → LEQG does NOT reach (b). Reject as a shortcut.\n- If structural ΔA (post-#4) → LEQG is meaningful as a sample-based realization of risk-sensitive (b).\n\n## References\n- `/Users/mll/Documents/Claude/Projects/clench/synthesis-5.md` §1 (typology of max), §5 (Whittle bridge), §9 Prediction 2.\n- `results/part2_5/synthesis_review.md` §11 (sequenced next steps).\n- Synthesis 5 tension #2 (this issue resolves it.)","files":null}]}